@[simp]
lemma nil_isAltPath (hM : G.IsMatching M) (x : α) : G.IsAltPath hM (.nil x) ↔ x ∈ V(G) := by
  simp [isAltPath_iff]
```

This lemma states that a trivial path (a single vertex) is an alternating path if and only if that vertex is in the graph. This is true by definition.

Next lemma:

```tactics
lemma IsAltPath.of_cons (h : G.IsAltPath hM (.cons x e P)) : G.IsAltPath hM P := by
  simp only [isAltPath_iff, cons_isPath_iff, WList.cons_edge] at h ⊢
  obtain ⟨⟨hP, hl, hx⟩, he⟩ := h
  exact ⟨hP, he.of_cons⟩
```

This lemma shows that if a path P' is obtained by adding an edge e at the front of another path P, and P' is an alternating path, then P is also an alternating path. This is true because the alternating property is preserved when removing the first edge.

Next lemma:

```tactics
@[simp]
lemma IsAltPath.tail (h : G.IsAltPath hM P) : G.IsAltPath hM P.tail := by
  match P with
  | .nil u => simp_all
  | .cons u e w => simp [h.of_cons]
```

This lemma states that if P is an alternating path, then the path obtained by removing the first vertex and edge of P is also an alternating path. This is true because the alternating property is preserved in the tail of the path.

Next lemma:

```tactics
lemma IsAltPath.suffix (h : G.IsAltPath hM P) (h' : P'.IsSuffix P) : G.IsAltPath hM P' :=
  h'.recOfTail (fun _ h ↦ h.tail) h
```

This lemma shows that if P is an alternating path and P' is a suffix of P, then P' is also an alternating path. This is true because the alternating property is preserved in the suffix of a path.

Next lemma:

```tactics
lemma IsAltPath.of_concat (h : G.IsAltPath hM (P.concat e x)) : G.IsAltPath hM P := by
  simp only [isAltPath_iff, concat_isPath_iff, WList.concat_edge, List.isChain_append,
    List.IsChain.singleton, Option.mem_def, List.head?_cons, Option.some.injEq, forall_eq',
    true_and] at h ⊢
  obtain ⟨⟨hP, hl, hx⟩, he, hlast⟩ := h
  refine ⟨hP, he⟩
```

This lemma states that if a path P' is obtained by concatenating two paths P₁ and P₂, and P' is an alternating path, then P₁ is also an alternating path. This is true because the alternating property is preserved in the first part of the concatenation.

