              by_contra hM
              have hdisj := M.disjoint heN hM
              simp [hvN] at hdisj
            simp [hvM]
```

For $w = v$, we need to show $v \in V(G, M \Delta E(P))$. This is true because $v \in E(P)$:

```tactics
          simp [hvM, P.mem_vertex]
```

We have shown that $S \cup \{v\} \subseteq V(G, M \Delta E(P))$. Therefore, $S \cup \{v\}$ is matchable:

```tactics
      exact ⟨M ∆ E(P), hM4, hM5⟩
```

This completes the proof of the third axiom. We have shown that if $S$ and $T$ are matchable with $|S| < |T|$, then there exists some $v \in T \setminus S$ such that $S \cup \{v\}$ is also matchable.

The rank of the matroid is $2\nu(G)$ because each edge in a matching contributes 2 to the total degree sum, and the maximum matching size $\nu(G)$ is the largest possible set of edges with no shared vertices. So the rank is $2 \cdot \nu(G)$.
