- Consider the symmetric difference $M_I \Delta M_J$. This forms a graph where each connected component is an alternating path or cycle.
- Since $|I| < |J|$, the number of vertices in $J \setminus I$ is greater than the number of vertices in $I \setminus J$.
- Therefore, there must be an alternating path in $M_I \Delta M_J$ that starts or ends in $J \setminus I$ and goes to $I \setminus J$.
- This path can be used to construct a new matching $M_I' = M_I \Delta E(P)$, where $P$ is the path, which will match $I \cup \{v\}$ for some $v \in J \setminus I$.

